sed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["L3 nerve root","L4 nerve root","L5 nerve root","S1 nerve root","S2 nerve root"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EL5 nerve root\u003C/strong\u003E is the main contributor to the common fibular nerve. This nerve innervates the short head of the biceps femoris muscle. Its terminal branches are the deep and superficial fibular nerves. The deep fibular nerve innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg, that is, the tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus and the extensor hallucis longus. These muscles are responsible for ankle dorsiflexion and extension of the toes. Compression of this nerve root typically causes weakness in foot dorsiflexion and toe extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other nerve roots have different primary functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL3 nerve root\u003C/strong\u003E mainly supplies knee extensors via the femoral nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL4 nerve root\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to knee extension and ankle inversion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES1 nerve root\u003C/strong\u003E primarily supplies ankle plantarflexors via the tibial nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES2 nerve root\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to hip extension and ankle plantarflexion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The L5 nerve root primarily contributes to the common fibular nerve which supplies the dorsiflexors of the foot.","The tibial nerve receives contributions mainly from L5, S1 and S2 nerve roots.","The sciatic nerve forms from the union of the tibial and common fibular nerves, containing fibres from L4-S3."],"references":["Moore et al. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 2017. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-28T10:28:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-28T10:28:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11891"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82119"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun